The large macroeconomic divergence
PARIS – "Global expansion has reached its peak," warns the OECD in its latest Economic Outlook, and performance could suffer if downward risks materialize.
The party isn't over yet: it is expected that global growth will continue in the years 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
Yet economists are famously bad at recognizing macroeconomic turning points, and the future course of the economy is difficult to assess.
Possible stumbling blocks abound: a more aggressive tightening of monetary policy, particularly in the United States; a further escalation of protectionism; an economic landing in China that turns out to be harsher than expected; and a resurgence of tensions within the Eurozone triggered by concerns regarding the fate of Italian government finances.
All of this, or indeed each of these developments individually, could intensify the downturn that has already begun.
A recession in the USA would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is already eyeing re-election in 2020, although such a development would not contradict established patterns.
Officially, the expansion began in June 2009, and with a duration until July 2019, it would have been the longest such phase in U.S. economic history.
Unemployment is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, the implementation of the economic policy measures of the Trump administration, consisting of substantial tax cuts and increased spending—that is, a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was intended to avert an impending depression—is not economically sensible.
This leaves the Federal Reserve with only two options: either it raises interest rates more sharply to offset the poorly timed stimulus measures, or it capitulates.
Such irresponsible cowardice between the American fiscal and monetary authorities, given the global repercussions of the U.S. interest rate cycle, increases the risk of instability even in the rest of the world.
A global recession would come too early for those countries whose recovery started late or was weak, or both.
An extreme example is Greece, where growth only picked up in 2017 and unemployment is still nearly 20 percent.
But Greece is not alone.
In Italy, the per capita GDP is no higher than it was in the middle of the 1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment is still significantly above the pre-crisis level.
The challenge lies in getting long-term unemployed individuals, who are at risk of losing their qualifications, back into employment.
To prevent lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international situation alone cannot solve their problems, but it would help maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is the German labor market, which is currently in a far better condition than in 2007.
In the western federal states, full employment prevails, and economic growth is increasingly dependent on immigration: in 2017, the net inflow – not including refugees, but migrants from other European countries – amounted to around 400,000 people.
In Japan, the United Kingdom, and Poland, the recovery was also characterized by the creation of many jobs.
Citizens complain about income, inequality, or rising house prices, but not about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis almost affected all developed economies at the same time.
Today, however, they do not appear in line either structurally or cyclically.
That is certainly alarming, as the emerging cooling of the world economy coincides with a time of increasing political fragility.
Trust in governments and institutions responsible for political decision-making is – quite understandably – extremely low.
Collective economic mismanagement would only further undermine this trust and fuel the already rising economic nationalism.
What is to be done now?
The list of tasks to be addressed starts in one's own country. In many countries where the labor market remains imbalanced, national measures are needed to strengthen economic potential and improve access to jobs.
In France, employers report a shortage of skilled workers despite an unemployment rate of 9 percent and reforms by President Emmanuel Macron.
To change this, comprehensive measures in the education sector are just as necessary as support for mobility, incentives for accepting jobs, and the opening up of protected sectors.
This is already happening.
In contrast, in Italy the governing coalition has initiated an economic stimulus program and simultaneously proposed measures to reduce the labor participation rate.
Among these are the reversal of the pension reform from 2011 and the introduction of a "citizen's income," which, in the case of inadequate planning or implementation, will lead to fewer people pursuing employment.
This political contradiction and, to a lesser extent, Italy's deviation from the European Union's budget rules is the real cause for concern.
The second priority is to establish a balance of risks.
For some time now, a political debate has been unfolding between political hawks and doves, with the former warning that the asset purchases by central banks and near-zero interest rates are fueling financial instability and inflation risks. Meanwhile, the doves' greatest concern is deflation.
Both are certainly real, although there is more reason to be concerned about deflation.
Real estate price bubbles can be contained through regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio of the loan amount to the property's value or between the loan amount and income.
With regard to inflation, the forecasts are regularly proven wrong.
So far, wages have slowly responded to the declining unemployment.
There is a justified fear of a possible sudden rise, but after so many years of subpar inflation, this risk can certainly be taken.
The collective costs of a temporary inflation overshoot pale in comparison to those of an early onset recession, which leads to lasting damage and a political counter-movement against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is by far the most difficult to achieve, particularly in the Eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a uniform policy for different national economies.
The standard recipe would be for the ECB to target the average inflation rate and to rely on national fiscal policy for fine-tuning the macroeconomic course.
Yet due to higher debts or remaining deficits, the countries that would need further growth are exactly those that have no fiscal policy room for maneuver.
Neither Greece nor Italy, indeed not even Spain or France, can currently consider a substantial economic stimulus program.
Without the possibility of cross-border transfers (which are also not included in the most recent agreement between France and Germany on a mini-eurozone budget), this is yet another reason why the ECB should act more boldly.
This would leave the governments of countries threatened by overheating with the task of cooling down their economies using fiscal measures, while the governments of countries still striving for economic improvement would be tasked with tapping into their economic potential.
There are numerous reasons to doubt that this is possible.
But it is the task of political decision-makers to manage risks, even if the risks of today are not the usual ones.
At stake is the resilience of the world economic system.
Despite favorable conditions, the first cracks are showing.
It must be prevented that they become cracks.
